// 📦 SUMMARY  
// This code builds: A Jenkins Declarative Pipeline with a single 'Deploy' stage. It pauses during execution to prompt the user for a deployment environment selection (`dev`, `staging`, or `prod`) and then passes that choice into a Groovy helper script for deployment.  
// Language/Platform: Jenkins Declarative Pipeline (Groovy syntax)  
// What you'll learn: Using `input` for user interaction, dynamic parameter handling, loading and calling external Groovy scripts.  
// Outcome: Jenkins pauses the pipeline for user input. Once an environment is selected, it executes `deployApp` with that environment as an argument.  
// Why this matters: Provides manual control for deployments to different environments—critical in real-world CI/CD workflows with approvals.  

pipeline {                                  // ✅ What it does: Declares the Jenkins Declarative Pipeline block.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Entry point for Jenkins to interpret and execute the pipeline.  

  agent any                                 // ✅ What it does: Runs the pipeline on any available Jenkins agent/node.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Keeps the pipeline flexible without tying it to a specific node label.  

  stages {                                  // ✅ What it does: Defines a sequence of stages (logical steps in the pipeline).  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Stages make the workflow modular, maintainable, and clear in Jenkins UI.  

    stage('Deploy') {                       // ✅ What it does: Declares a stage named 'Deploy'.  
      steps {                               // ✅ What it does: Lists the actions to execute in this stage.  

        script {                            // ✅ What it does: Enters a Groovy script block for custom logic.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Required for imperative code, user input, and calling external scripts.  

          def userInput = input(            // ✅ What it does: Prompts user for input during pipeline execution.  
            id: 'envInput',                 // ✅ Provides a unique ID for this input step (important for retries/resumes).  
            message: 'Select Environment',  // ✅ Message displayed in Jenkins UI to ask user for deployment target.  
            parameters: [                    // ✅ Defines the list of parameters the user will be asked for.  
              choice(                        // ✅ Creates a dropdown choice input for the user.  
                name: 'ENV',                 // ✅ Name of the parameter (referenced later as userInput.ENV).  
                choices: ['dev', 'staging', 'prod'],  // ✅ Available deployment environments to choose from.  
                description: 'Deployment Environment' // ✅ Helpful description shown to the user in Jenkins UI.  
              )
            ]
          )                                 // 🧠 Why it matters: Pipeline halts here until a user makes a selection and clicks “Proceed”.  

          echo "Deploying to ${userInput}"   // ✅ What it does: Logs the selected environment to Jenkins console output.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Confirms to the operator which environment was selected.  

          def gv = load 'jenkins-jobs/script.groovy'  
                                           // ✅ What it does: Loads an external Groovy helper script from workspace folder.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Separates deployment logic into reusable scripts, keeping Jenkinsfile clean.  

          gv.deployApp(userInput)           // ✅ What it does: Calls the deployApp() function from script.groovy with user’s chosen environment.  
                                           // 🧠 Why it matters: Enables dynamic deployments to different environments without modifying the Jenkinsfile.  
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
